Use Analysis of Competing Hypotheses (ACH) on the claim "Actor X conducted the cyber intrusion." Step 1: enumerate hypotheses — H1: Actor X did it; H2: Actor Y (false-flag) did it mimicking X; H3: an insider did it; H4: an unaffiliated criminal group did it. Step 2: list evidence — E1: malware shares code with X's known toolkit; E2: command-and-control IPs previously attributed to X; E3: intrusion occurred during X's working hours/timezone; E4: target had no obvious value to X; E5: a leaked X toolkit is publicly available. Step 3: build a matrix and score each evidence item as Consistent (C), Inconsistent (I), or Not Applicable (N/A) with each hypothesis; the discriminator is inconsistency, not consistency. Step 4: E1 and E2 are C with H1 but also C with H2 (toolkit is leaked, IPs can be reused), so they have low diagnostic value; E4 is I with H1 (weak motive) and C with H2/H4; E3 is C with H1, I with H4. Step 5: the hypothesis with the fewest inconsistencies wins — here H2 (false-flag) is not eliminated and arguably better explains E4 than H1. Step 6: identify key assumptions (that timezone implies nationality) and sensitivity — flipping that assumption shifts the verdict, so confidence in H1 should be downgraded to "low-to-moderate." Step 7: specify collection gaps that would discriminate (operator-language artifacts, build timestamps, victim selection pattern) and revisit when collected. Conclusion: the claim "X did it" is not adequately supported; ACH elevates H2 as a serious competing hypothesis pending further evidence.
